               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18420509-1717-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1717-18420509 t18420509-1717-offence-1 t18420509-1717-verdict-1"></join>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184205090271"></xptr>
               <p>1717. <persName id="def1-1717-18420509" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1717-18420509" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1717-18420509" type="age" value="38"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1717-18420509" type="surname" value="COLLARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1717-18420509" type="given" value="LUCY"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">LUCY COLLARD</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18420509-1717-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420509-1717-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420509-1717-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>for stealing, on the <rs id="t18420509-cd-258" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420509-1717-offence-1 t18420509-cd-258"></join>5th of March</rs>, 1 shirt, value 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 sheet, value 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; and 2 handkerchiefs, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18420509-name-1607" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1607" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1607" type="surname" value="HAYDEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1607" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420509-1717-offence-1 t18420509-name-1607"></join>William Hayden</persName>, her master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420509-name-1608" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1608" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1608" type="surname" value="HAYDEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1608" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM HAYDEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a haberdasher—the prisoner was my servant of all-work, and had 8<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a year. On Sunday, the 24th of April I missed some things, which made me look to see if any thing else was gone, and I missed a sheet—I told her I would not be satisfied till I had got the sheet—in consequence of what she said to me I found the shirt, sheet, and two handkerchiefs at Mr. Turner's, a pawnbroker, in Walworth-road—I went there in consequence of seeing the duplicate in her hand—she said she had pawned the sheet—she was not willing for me to get it out, she wished to get it out herself—I said, "You have no money to get it out"—she said she would pawn some of her own things to get it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How came you to know she had the duplicate? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> We said no<lb></lb>thing about the sheet till Monday morning—I then pressed her to tell me where it was—she said she knew nothing about it—I said nobody had ac<lb></lb>cess to it but herself—then she said she had pawned it, and produced the duplicate—she said there was only the sheet and her own shawl—I went to Turner's, and found the articles—I had seen the shirt safe about a fort<lb></lb>before—the handkerchiefs were in the back-warehouse—I knew the papers they were in were there, but I did not look into them—the police<lb></lb>man found a pair of gloves, which I kept in the same chest of drawers up stairs with the shirt—the drawer was found broken open on the Sunday night—I had seen it safe that afternoon—I always kept it locked—I do not think I had opened it that day—I gave her into custody on the 25th of April.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long had she been in your service? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Since the 21st of February—she came as a single woman, I have since found she is married—she told me after a long time that she had pawned the sheet and produced the duplicate, and said she had pawned a shawl of her own at the same time, but that did not prove true—I am a widower—my family consists of a servant and four children—the prisoner did not say she had pledged the things for the purpose of send<lb></lb>ing money down to her son at Bristol—I let her have a sovereign on the 15th of March, and afterwards 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. on the 20th, to send her son—I saw Turner's name on the duplicate—I think I can swear to the handkerchiefs when I see them—the prisoner said she had brought them from Bristol with her after we found them—she did not deny the shirt and sheet being mine.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420509-name-1609" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1609" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1609" type="surname" value="GREAVES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1609" type="given" value="CHRISTOPHER THOMAS"></interp>CHRISTOPHER THOMAS GREAVES</persName>
                  </hi>. I am apprentice to Turner, a pawn<lb></lb>broker. I have a shirt, sheet, and two silk handkerchiefs—I wrote the duplicate produced for it on the 5th of March, for 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—they were pledged by the woman in the name of Ann Hemmings—I cannot speak to the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HAYDEN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> This shirt, sheet, and handkerchiefs I can swear to—the shirt has my name on it—I know the handkerchiefs, in consequence of their being in a damp place they got spotted, and I altered the price of them all, and put a fresh mark on them—the mark is not here—I produce one of the same quality with the same sort of spots on it—I also know the gloves.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Except the spots there is nothing uncommon about them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They are the same kind of handkerchief—after we missed the sheet she told my daughter she had pawned it—she did not say my daugh<lb></lb>ter had authorised her to do so—I had said before that that I would find out where it was.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184205090272"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420509-name-1610" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1610" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1610" type="surname" value="LLOYD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-1610" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN LLOYD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. I was called to the house, went up stairs for the prisoner, and told her the prosecutor suspected she had robbed him—she produced the duplicate—I asked if she objected to my searching her boxes—she said, "No," and gave me two keys—I found nothing in her boxes—I took her to the station—she was searched there, and this pair of gloves found on her—she said she picked them up in the room.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> She told you, did not she, that she pawned the things intending to get them again? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18420509-1717-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420509-1717-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420509-1717-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
                     <hi rend="smallCaps">GUILTY</hi>. Aged 38.—<hi rend="italic">Recommended to mercy.</hi>
                  </rs>—
<rs id="t18420509-1717-punishment-269" type="punishmentDescription">
